Choices:  B: fire C: water D: stone<n>Output: C: water<n><n>#import the libraries<n>import sys<n>import unittest<n><n>ver = sys.version.split('.')<n>if int(ver[0]) < 3:<n>    import unittest2 as unittest<n>else:<n>    import unittest as unittest<n><n>class UnittestTestCase(unittest.TestCase):<n><n>    def assertTrue(self,value, msg=None):<n>        if type(value) == bool:<n>            self.assertTrue(value)<n>        else:<n>            self.fail(msg)<n><n>    def assertFalse(self,value,msg=None):<n>        self.assertFalse(value)<n><n>    def test_multiple(self):<n>        answers = [21255, 200121, 395, 395] <n>        for answers, output in [xrange(0,len(answers)),xrange(0, len(output))] :<n>            a = answers[output]<n>            b = output[output]<n>            #print a<n>            #print b<n>            self.assertEqual(a, b)<n><n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    try:<n>        x = UnittestTestCase()<n>        unittest.main()<n>    except SystemExit as e:<n>        sys.exit(e)<n>

They have hands that they can use to get to the top of what? Choices:  A: outside B: hill C: jungle D: rocky hillside E: tree<n>Output: E: tree<n><n>Input:John hated mosquitoes.  It wasn't the bloodsucking that he disliked, it was that the insects made what? Choices:  A: fly B: buzz C: move D: honey E: help flowers pollenate<n>Output:		B: buzz<n><n><!--<n>[![Join the chat at https://gitter.im/GoPro-open-source/Lobby](https://badges.gitter.im/Join%20Chat.svg)](https://gitter.im//GoPro-open-space?utm_source=badge&utm_medium=button&utm_campaign=pr-badge&utm-content=badge)<n>--><n><!-- Markdown link & img dfn's --><n>[couchpotato(https://github.com/mimibotanica/couchpotato)](https://github.com//mimibotaneca/couchpotato)<n>[couchpotatotorrent(https://github. com/mimibotancita/couchpotatotrent)]()<n>[http://mimicreel.com(https://github).](http://mimicrie.ncom)(http) [mimicreel(https://mimicreelse.com)](https://github)<n><!-- Prettier --><n>```python<n>#!/usr/bin/python<n>import json<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def isLongestIncreasingPath(self, graph):<n>        nodes = list(graph.keys())<n>        for i in range(len(nodes) - 2,-1,-1):<n>            path = []<n>            path.append(nodes[i])<n>            longest_path = 0<n>            for j in range(i+1,len(nodes)):<n>                if (not graph[nodes[i]] and not graph[nodes[j]]):<n>                    break<n>                if (graph[nodes[i]] == True and graph[nodes[j+1]] == True):<n>                    path.append(nodes [j+1])<n>                    if len(path) >  longest_path:<n>                        longest_path = len(path)<n>            if longest_path > 4:<n>                return True<n>            path.delete(path[-1])<n>        if longest_path >2:<n>            return True<n>    return False<n>```<n>

She will have to return and apologize to someone.  To whom? Choices:  <p>Person:  A: mother B: father C: sibling D: teacher E: friend F: husband G: boyfriend H. best friend<n>Output (F): husband   (G): boyfriend   <br><n>You might think that (H) best friend was the best choice, but (Y) friend would have been more accurate.  You can say that Y refers to a friend, but not a best friend.  B is a good choice, but not an accurate choice.  The word "boyfriend" is a good clue.  So, the answer is G.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The machine was very intricate, it was quite an what? Choices:  A: box B: apparatus C: appliance D: wash dishes E: implement<n>Output: B: apparatus<n><n>Input: Where do you get petrol? Choices:  A: burn hot B: fuel tank C: burn hot D: car E: gas station<n>Output: E: gas station<n><n>Input: Where might a television used at night be? Choices:  A: cabinet B: house C: apartment D: bedroom E: woods<n>Output: D: bedroom<n><n>Input: The knowledge was expensive to get, where was it being gained? Choices:  A: university B: book C: field D: meeting E: class<n>Output: A: university<n><n>Input: Where are small grapes likely to be found? Choices:  A: lunch box B: food store C: wine country D: kitchen E: raisins<n>Output: C: wine country<n><n>Input: The painter explained how he never achieved a flawless portrait, he said this was because all people are what? Choices:  A: imperfect B: disfigured C: damaged D: flawed E: defective<n>Output: A: imperfect<n><n>Input: If you're betting with a shark, where are you likely playing? Choices:  A: aquarium B: mediterranean sea C: south pacific D: pool hall E: pacific ocean<n>Output: D: pool hall<n><n>Input: Marmot's can be found in high places.  They have hands that they can use to get to the top of what? Choices:  A: outside B: hill C: jungle D: rocky hillside E: tree<n>Output: E: tree<n><n>Input:What will happen to skin pinched in something? Choices:  A: feel cold B: feel pressure C: feel bumpy D: itches E: feel clammy<n>Output:		E: feel clamant<n><n>Input: Where will you most likely find a bird? Choices:  a. On the roof b. In the window c. On the beach d. In a car e. Under the moon<n>Output:  c. On the Beach<n>Input: What are you most likely to buy something from a man wearing? Choices: 1. a hat 2. a tie 3. a pocket watch 4. a handkerchief 5. a pocket<n>Output: 5. a pocket <n><n><n>### Solution:<n>For Example<n>The input string is "The machine was very intricate."<n>Checking the definition of "intricate" from the dictionary, we get <n><n>```python<n>> intricate:  intricately formed or made<n>```<n><n>I think a best choice would be "aparatus"<n><n><n>### Code:<n><n>```python<n>import re<n><n>text1 = "The machine was very complicated"<n>text2 = "It was very confusing"<n>text3 = "Walking in high heels was a pain"<n>text4 = "My boss was a real jerk"<n>text5 = "My roommate is an alien"<n><n>def is_adverb(word):<n>    if re.match(['\d'], word) or re.match(r'\w+','adjective', flags=re.IGNORECASE):<n>        return True<n>    else:<n>        return False<n><n>def is_noun(word):<n>    #this is not perfect<n>    #a few good tests, including the one for "cant/wont"<n>    if any((x == 'a' or x == 'e') for x in word): #e = element<n>        return True<n><n>def getNouns():<n>    nouns = []<n>    index = -1<n>    for i in re.findall("\\w+", text1 + text2 + text3 + text4 + text5):<n>        if re.match(r"t\w+\w+e\w+", i):<n>            index += 1<n><n>    while(1):<n>        index += 1<n>        word = re.findall("t\w+\w+\w+",text1+text2+text3+text4+text
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The machine was very intricate, it was quite an what? Choices:  A: aquarium B: mediterranean sea C: south pacific D: pool hall E: pacific ocean<n>Output: D: pool hall<n><n>Input: Marmot's can be found in high places.  They have hands that they can use to get to the top of what? Choices:  A: outside B: hill C: jungle D: rocky hillside E: tree<n>Output: E: tree<n><n>Input:Blood isn't usually spilled during what sport that doesn't allow the use of hands? Choices:  A: soccer game B: capillaries C: ball D: animals E: person<n>Output:		A: soccer game<n><n>Input: If a bird eats something that's too big, the crop can burst. Which of these might be the next step for the bird? Choices: <n>  A: eat a smaller meal B: crop C: burp D: vomit E: diarrhea<n>Output: D: vomit<n><n>Input: Dogs and people have different types of what? Choices A: noses B: eyes C: ears D: hair E: language<n>Output: B: eyes<n><n>Input: Where does a robotic arm often be seen? Choices:  E: television<n>Output: C: manufacturing plant<n><n>Input: Baking a cookie on the stove requires doing what? Choices: burning gasoline<n>Output: putting in the oven<n><n><n><n>## Solution<n><n>**A:** If it what, it will be. If it isn't, it won't, like an if/then rule. The word 'what' in the dictionary only means something, not nothing. It's necessary to make a statement, even if it's a lie or a joke or just to fill space. Without an 'if', no one would know you were talking about something unless you said exactly what you meant, like a person name, and that would make the sentence longer to speak.<n><n>

Choices:  M: Marlin B: Michael E: Mark C: Marlin<n>Output: C: Marlin<n><n># Solution<n>from nltk.corpus import stopwords, words<n>s_word_list =words('S.')<n>s_stopwords = stopwords.words('S.') <n><n># Check wordlist<n># s_word_list = 'hello'<n># s_stopwords = 'how are you?'<n><n>def solution(sentence):<n>    sentence_list = nltk.sent_tokenize(sentence)<n>    sentences = nltk.find_stopwords(sentence_list, s_stopwords)    <n>    for word in sentences:<n>        sentence_list[0] =''.join([word.lower()])<n>    sentences = nLTK.corpus_tokenize(sentences)<n>    return [sentences][0]<n><n>## Instruction:<n>## Print the first 3 lines of the document.<n>## Expect Answer Format:<n>## [['A wash dishes'], ['An implement'], ['E a wash dishes']]<n><n># Solution<n>import io<n>f = io.StringIO(testcases)<n>words = f.read().splitlines()<n>word_list = words[0::3]<n>print(s_word_list[word_list[0]])    <n>print(s_stopwords[word_list[1]])<n>print(s_words_list[word_t[2]<n><n># Instruction:<n>## Answer the question<n>## Expect Answer:<n>## A, E<n><n># Solution<n>f = io.File('testcases.txt', mode="r")<n>f.readline() # read the first line.<n>answer,_,_=testcases[-1][:3]<n>print(answer)<n># 'E a wash dish'<n><n># Instruction<n>## Answer the question <n>## Expect Answer :<n>## E<n><n># Solution <n>f = io.file('testcases.txt','r')<n>lines_read = f.readlines()<n>print

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The machine was very intricate, it was quite an what? Choices:  A: box B: apparatus C: appliance D: wash dishes E: implement<n>Output: B: apparatus<n><n>Input: Where do you get petrol? Choices:  A: burn hot B: fuel tank C: burn hot D: car E: gas station<n>Output: E: gas station<n><n>Input: Where might a television used at night be? Choices:  A: university B: book C: field D: meeting E: class<n>Output: A: university<n><n>Input: Where are small grapes likely to be found? Choices:  A: lunch box B: food store C: wine country D: kitchen E: raisins<n>Output: C: wine country<n><n>Input: The painter explained how he never achieved a flawless portrait, he said this was because all people are what? Choices:  A: imperfect B: disfigured C: damaged D: flawed E: defective<n>Output: A: imperfect<n><n>Input: If you're betting with a shark, where are you likely playing? Choices:  A: aquarium B: mediterranean sea C: south pacific D: pool hall E: pacific ocean<n>Output: D: pool hall<n><n>Input: Marmot's can be found in high places.  They have hands that they can use to get to the top of what? Choices:  A: outside B: hill C: jungle D: rocky hillside E: tree<n>Output: E: tree<n><n>Input:The movie had many a song and dance, it was a what? Choices:  A: bollywood B: record C: musical D: jukebox E: napster<n>Output:		A: bollywood<n><n>Input: What about the bible is the most interesting to the historian? Choices:  R: that it's never lost R: that it has the answers for everything R: that it includes the truth R: that it includes answers to all possible truths R: everything in there will be of interest to the historian<n>Output: R: everything in there is of interest to the historian <n><n>### Your Own Code<n><n>My solution: <n>```python<n><n>a = input().replace(' ','')<n>n = len(a)<n>if abs(a[n])>abs(a[a.index(' ')+1:n]):<n>	print("Answer: A" + " " + " "+ " " + " " + " "  + " " + " ") <n>	<n>elif abs(a[n] - a[0]) > 2 and abs(a[1] - a[n]) > 2:<n>	print("Answer : B" + " " +"  " + "  " + "  ")<n><n><n>elif abs(a[:n]-a[-n:]) > 2 and a[:n]==a[-n:] :<n>	if len(a) % 2 ==0:<n>		print("Answer:C" + " " +  "+ " + " "+ "  " + " ")<n>	else:<n>		print ("Answer:D " + " + " + " "+ " ")<n><n>elif len(a)%2==1 and a [0] in a[1:]:<n>	print("Answer E" + "  " + "+ " + "  ")	<n><n>else:<n>	print("No Answer " + "  "+ " + "  ") <n>	<n>```<n><n>

Choices:  Too many:  2 Incorrect  Out: 2<n><n>##<n><n># Problem:<n><n>Write a program that plays a game of "21 questions" with a human.<n><n>The game has the human beanspotting a person out of a list of ten persons by asking questions.  You play this game as the computer.<n><n>You'll receive a list of ten names (one at a time), a random person being picked at the end of the list, and several questions.  If<n>you're asked the question on the list ("Does your friend have a birthday?"), you must answer yes, no, or I don't know.  If the<n>question is about something you know, you should answer yes.  If the question is something you don't know, you must answer no.  You<n>should try to avoid saying "I don't know."<n><n>The computer will be the interviewer and ask questions of the human, which must answer yes or no or have no answer(n/a).  Each person<n>gets a turn for questions.<n><n># Example questions that the computer can ask (the correct answers are already in bold):<n><n># Who is the prime minister of Canada?<n><n>Who is president of US?<n><n>Who is the minister of agriculture in the USA?<n><n>Who was the last president of the Soviet Union?<n><n>What is the capital of Peru?<n><n>Who defeated Germany in WWII?<n><n>What is Canada's largest city?<n><n>What are China's neighbors?<n><n><n># Instructions:<n><n>For this project:<br /><n>1. Fork this repository in your account.<n>2. Open the.java file and write your Java code.<n>3. Run the program as a unit test and make sure its output is correct.<n>4. If you're asked a question and don't know the answer, you must say "I don't<n>know." to win.<n>5. If you give the correct answer, the game will be won.<br /><n>If you give an incorrect the game will be lost.<n><n># Output should look like:<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The machine was very intricate, it was quite an what? Choices:  A: box B: apparatus C: appliance D: wash dishes E: implement<n>Output: B: apparatus<n><n>Input: Where do you get petrol? Choices:  A: burn hot B: fuel tank C: burn hot D: car E: gas station<n>Output: E: gas station<n><n>Input: Where might a television used at night be? Choices:  A: cabinet B: house C: apartment D: bedroom E: woods<n>Output: D: bedroom<n><n>Input: The knowledge was expensive to get, where was it being gained? Choices:  A: university B: book C: field D: meeting E: class<n>Output: A: university<n><n>Input: Where are small grapes likely to be found? Choices:  A: lunch box B: food store C: wine country D: kitchen E: raisins<n>Output: C: wine country<n><n>Input: The painter explained how he never achieved a flawless portrait, he said this was because all people are what? Choices:  A: imperfect B: disfigured C: damaged D: flawed E: defective<n>Output: A: imperfect<n><n>Input: If you're betting with a shark, where are you likely playing? Choices:  A: aquarium B: mediterranean sea C: south pacific D: pool hall E: pacific ocean<n>Output: D: pool hall<n><n>Input: Marmot's can be found in high places.  They have hands that they can use to get to the top of what? Choices:  A: outside B: hill C: jungle D: rocky hillside E: tree<n>Output: E: tree<n><n>Input:What home entertainment equipment requires cable? Choices:  A: radio shack B: substation C: cabinet D: television E: desk<n>Output:		A: radio shack<n><n>#### Solution:<n>```py<n>import math<n>n=math.floor(input())<n><n>if n==0 or n==1:<n>	return 0<n>if n==3:<n>	return 1<n>if (n+1)*(n+2)*(n+3)%10<0:<n>	return 2<n>if (n+2)*(3+2)*(n-1)%10<10:<n>	return(3)<n>return 4<n>```

Choices: 1 A: fire 2 B: water 3 C: food 4 D: humans<n>Output: D: humans<n><n>### Notes in python:<n>```<n>from collections import namedtuple<n>Grammar = namedtuple("Grammar", ["grammar"]) # The "Grammar" class for the named tuples for the grammar<n>grammars = [ # grammar tuples<n>    Grammar(["is"], [1, 2, 3, 2]),<n>    Grammar( ["was"], [2, 1]),<n>     Grammar(["what"],[1, 2]),<n>     Grammar([ "used"],[2]),<n>     Grammary(["where"],[1]),<n>     Grammary([ "at", "night"],[2, 1]),   <n>     Grammary([],[1]),<n>    <n>]<n><n><n>def is_acceptable(word, grammar):<n>    # The function to determine if a word is grammatically correct<n>    acceptable = False<n>    if (grammar.grammar[0] == word):<n>        acceptable = True<n>    if (is_acceptable_one_of(word, grammar)):<n>        acceptable = True <n>    if is_acceptable(grammar.grammar[-1], grammar)<n>        acceptable = True # the last word should acceptable too<n>    return acceptable<n><n><n>def isAcceptable_one_of (word, grammar):<n>     acceptable = False <n>     length = 0 <n>     if len(grammar.grammer) > 0:<n>         lastword = grammar.grammer[-1] <n>             lastIndex = len(lastword) <n>             totalIndex = len(word) <n>             if (totalIndex == lastIndex and word[0] == lastword[0]):<n>                 print(word, "matches", lastword)<n>                 acceptable = True<n>             increment = True <n>             while (increment and length < 4):<n>                 # check if 0th index is the same<n>                 firstIndex = length<n>                 lastIndex = length-2<n>                 if (lastword[length] == word[firstIndex]):<n>                     print("first match", firstIndex, lastword

Choices: 1. open 2. closed 3. together 4. inside 5. without having to find it<n>Output: 3. together<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>```python<n>a = ["box", "apparatus", "appliance", "wash dishes", "implement", "hot", "fuel tank", "burn hot", "car", "gas station", "bedroom", "university", "wine country", "lunch box", "food store", "pool hall", "tree", "water cooler", "beach", "coal"]<n>b = ["box", "fuel tank","car","gas station", "lunch box","food store","pool hall", "water cooler","beach","coal"]<n><n>for i in range(0,100):<n>    print("Please input a word associated with the above items, followed by your preferred answer option:")<n><n>    word = input()<n>    word_b = word.split(" ")<n>    answer_b = ""<n>    for word_i in word_b:<n>        if word_i in b:<n>            answer_b = b.index(word_i)<n>    print("What is your answer?:",b[answer_b])<n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The machine was very intricate, it was quite an what? Choices:  A: box B: apparatus C: appliance D: wash dishes E: implement<n>Output: B: apparatus<n><n>Input: Where do you get petrol? Choices:  A: burn hot B: fuel tank C: burn hot D: car E: gas station<n>Output: E: gas station<n><n>Input: Where might a television used at night be? Choices:  A: cabinet B: house C: apartment D: bedroom E: woods<n>Output: D: bedroom<n><n>Input: The knowledge was expensive to get, where was it being gained? Choices:  A: university B: book C: field D: meeting E: class<n>Output: A: university<n><n>Input: Where are small grapes likely to be found? Choices:  A: lunch box B: food store C: wine country D: kitchen E: raisins<n>Output: C: wine country<n><n>Input: The painter explained how he never achieved a flawless portrait, he said this was because all people are what? Choices:  A: imperfect B: disfigured C: damaged D: flawed E: defective<n>Output: A: imperfect<n><n>Input: If you're betting with a shark, where are you likely playing? Choices:  A: aquarium B: mediterranean sea C: south pacific D: pool hall E: pacific ocean<n>Output: D: pool hall<n><n>Input: Marmot's can be found in high places.  They have hands that they can use to get to the top of what? Choices:  A: outside B: hill C: jungle D: rocky hillside E: tree<n>Output: E: tree<n><n>Input:The policemen wanted to clear the scene of the accident, so what did they do to traffic? Choices:  A: hurry along B: direct traffic C: help D: force open door E: corner thief<n>Output:		A: hurry along<n><n>Input: How do people say there is little space in something? Choices:  B: full C: cluttered D: spare E: cramped<n>Output: B: full<n><n>Input: How can one describe people with different interests? Choices:  D: mixed E: confused<n>Output: D: mixed<n><n>Input: The store hated the lack of parking space so what did they do about it? Choices:  C: they expanded  D: they closed<n>Output: C: they expanded<n><n># Solution 1<n>import re<n>import numpy as np<n><n><n>def solution_1():<n>    pattern = {'a': 'box', 'b': 'apparatus', 'c': 'appliance', 'd': 'washdishes', 'e': 'implement'<n>          ,'f': 'gasstation', 'g': 'car', 'h': 'fueltank', 'i': 'bedroom', 'j': 'university', 'k': 'cabinet',<n>           'l': 'lunchbox','m': 'class', 'n': 'woods', 'o': 'winecountry', 'p': 'raisins',<n>           'q': 'poolhall', 'r': 'aquarium','s': 'jungle',<n>           't': 'tree', 'u': 'hill', 'v': 'hillside',<n>           'w': 'full',<n>           'x':'mixed',<n>           'y': 'cramped'}<n><n>    lines = []<n>    for line in open('input.txt').readlines():<n>        text = " ".join(line.split()[:-1])<n>        lines.append(text)<n><n>    print(json.dumps(lines))<n><n>    for line in lines:<n>        for pattern_pair in pattern.items():<n>            line = re.sub('|'.join((pattern_pair[0], pattern_pair[1])), pattern_pair[1], line)<n>        print(line)<n><n>    print('Done!')<n><n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    solution_1()<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The machine was very intricate, it was quite an what? Choices:  A: box B: apparatus C: appliance D: wash dishes E: implement<n>Output: B: apparatus<n><n>Input: Where do you get petrol? Choices:  A: burn hot B: fuel tank C: burn hot D: car E: gas station<n>Output: E: gas station<n><n>Input: Where might a television used at night be? Choices:  A: cabinet B: house C: apartment D: bedroom E: woods<n>Output: D: bedroom<n><n>Input: The knowledge was expensive to get, where was it being gained? Choices:  A: university B: book C: field D: meeting E: class<n>Output: A: university<n><n>Input: Where are small grapes likely to be found? Choices:  A: lunch box B: food store C: wine country D: kitchen E: raisins<n>Output: C: wine country<n><n>Input: The painter explained how he never achieved a flawless portrait, he said this was because all people are what? Choices:  A: imperfect B: disfigured C: damaged D: flawed E: defective<n>Output: A: imperfect<n><n>Input: If you're betting with a shark, where are you likely playing? Choices:  A: aquarium B: mediterranean sea C: south pacific D: pool hall E: pacific ocean<n>Output: D: pool hall<n><n>Input: Marmot's can be found in high places.  They have hands that they can use to get to the top of what? Choices:  A: outside B: hill C: jungle D: rocky hillside E: tree<n>Output: E: tree<n><n>Input:Bob needs a level to hang a shelf but cant find one in his home. Where would he go to get one? Choices:  A: glass of water B: build evenly C: garage D: carpenter's shop E: video game<n>Output:		C: garage<n><n>###### Solution<n><n>```<n>Input:<n>"The machine was very intricate it was quite on what? Choices (A) box (B) apparatus (C) appliance (D) wash dishes (E) implement"<n><n>case A: box"  box",<n>case B: apparatus:	" apparatus "<n>case C: appliance:" appliance  "<n>case D:" wash dishes":" wash dishes "<n>case E: implement:" implement "<n><n>Output:<n>B: apparatus<n><n>```<n><n>##### Explanation:<n><n>```<n>Instead of using the word " What ", we used the word "on"  and wrote the words that followed the "was" in brackets, separated by a semicolon.<n><n>It is like how we used the sentence " what are you doing? ".<n><n>As shown in the image as, the machine is 3 words. So, the words following should also be 3.<n><n><n>Instead of using only one word to describe the machine, we used two words to describe. The second word "intricate" is placed in brackets.<n><n>In python, we should take care to input the  brackets by using a space in between.<n><n>```<n><n>Input:<n>"Where do you get petrol? Choices (A)" B" fuel tank" (C) " burn hot" (D) "car" (E) "gas station"<n><n>case A(B)<n>case B(C)<n>case C(D)<n>case D(E)<n>case E(D)<n><n>Output:<n>E, D, D, D,D<n><n>Instead of writing the words that follows in brackets, we used the brackets where we expected the words to follow. This is because we gave only 2 choices, and it is not possible to put words in between two choices. So, we wrote each word in a separate line and used the brackets where we wanted to use the new word.<n>Instead of using a single word to describe a choice, we used 2 words to describe ( petrol). Thus, the second word "station" in the choice goes in "brackets"<n><n>Input:<n>“Where are small grapes are likely to be found? Choices (A"  B"  C) D “lunch"

Choices:  *1 day * 2 hours * 2 days * 2 weeks * 1 year<n><n>#### Solution:<n>Solution: In programming, we use the keyword 'FOR' to specify the condition. 'FOR' has a simple syntax:<n>```if condition<n>for count in range(condition,condition)<n>{<n>    code<n>}<n>```In our question, we have to find out after how many hours/days the programmer will use the program. Let’s take the condition as days and count in range as 1.<n><n>The code to do it:<n>```<n><n>if condition == 24(condition taken as hours and 24 is a day) :<n>    print("1 hours")<n>else : <n>    print("less than 1 hour")<n><n>```<n><n>#### Solution: - [Code](Code.py)<n>

Choices:  A: freeway B: radio C: wires D: computer network E: electrical circuit<n>Output:		D: computer network<n><n>Answer: A computer network is defined as "a group of computers linked together for communication and sharing resources. "  We should also mention what a computer is. "A computer is an electronic device, operating under the control of instructions stored in its own memory that can accept data (input), manipulate (process) the data according to specified rules, produce results (output), and store the results for future use."<n><n>Therefore, a computer network is a group of computers together that can communicate and connect to transfer data to and from. It is very possible to share files because one computer can be sent files that another computer can then access.<n>

Initially all values are set to 0.<n><n>Each turn consists of a player entering the coordinates of a tile to traverse to.  The player will provide each coordinate as an integer from 0 to 9.  This means only the player will be able to go first.  The computer will make all future moves.<n><n>Once a coordinate has been provided, the next closest edge value will be computed and provided to the player for selection of the next tile to traverse to.<n><n>A turn can be canceled once made by typing "end;"<n>Next, compute the closest edge value.<n>This is the distance from the player's current position that a single tile can be traversed across.  Next, check if the player has moved past 90°.<n>If they have, the game is over due to the player going beyond what is possible when viewed from the horizontal plane.<n>On the other hand, if they have not moved past the edge of the tile, next check if the next tile is the opposite of the current tile they are on.<n>If the tile is the reverse of the one they are on now, the player los
